<Content>Reviews are Misleading I travel quite a bit and like the Hyatt, Marriot, Hilton styles of hotels. I am not too picky, but also I don't settle for 2nd best if I can help it. The reviews on Trip Advisor and Expedia made this place seem top of the line. And for the $160 a night city view I thought I will totally try this hotel out. I got 2 rooms, for 7 of us. We usually stay at the Waikiki Marriot, but decided on this (and saving about $80 a night).BOY WERE WE CRAZY TO DO THIS! We checked in at 10pm after a long direct flight from Az to HI. We were NOT happy once in the room. The lobby looked great, but once upstairs I was not happy. We had 2 adjoining rooms and they both were so different, yet the same. Their set up  lay out was different, but the element was the same. Lots of weird colored stains on the carpet, couch, headboard and comforter. Then a musty old smell. I really had a huge fear of bedbugs while staying here, and I have NEVER had that feeling before at any other hotel. Room service stops at 10pm and all shops downstairs are closed. No mini bar. So we went to bed with no food or drinks. The bathroom was TINY. And the shower is 1/2 the size of a regular one, but with a door that can barely open and the shower itself looks like it had been shipped over from a 3rd World Country Hotel. The toilet paper holder fell off the wall when my son went to pull the piece of toilet paper off. The view of the city was of construction. We were scared to lean on the railing, so fear it may fall.Overall it is all very very old, and I know they are renovating slowly...but man according to reviews, this place should have been nicer. I mean we are on this great family Hawaiian vacation  to be presented with this dumpy room that looks like a heard of frat boys went crazy in is dumbfounded. I could expect this from a hotel under $100 a night. But an Outrigger hotel that is on the beach, I would not have guessed. This is really was a $40 truck stop room. Don't get me wrong the restaurant, location  lobby are NICE...not the rooms. Or at least the city view.So after 1 night we checked out  went to the Marriot Waikiki Beach Hotel, which was HEAVENLY. I was very happy once there. I also was told there was 3 other families that moved their stay from the Outrigger within the last 24 hours.So lesson is, $160 on the beach in Waikiki will look like a $40 truck stop room. Now $220 will look like a luxury hotel  make you enjoy your vacation. It is all about what you can afford I guess, but the reviews making this place seem luxurious are totally FALSE. Beware if you are like me and enjoy a nice hotel with great amenities. 
