<Content>Outtrigger Reef on the Beach not too bad We literally just got back from the Reef today and are back home. After reading all these reviews I wasn't sure what to expect, but it turned out not too bad after all. The employees are more then friendly, we were honeymooning and they sent us a bottle of champange and macadamia nuts complientary which was sweet. When we got to our room though, I wasn't too pleased. It was a standard room, not even a balcony. I didn't really feel like I was in Hawaii it just seemed like a standard Holiday Inn, except the difference is Holiday Inn's are $60 a night, unlike this $255 a room. So after a few complaints to my husband, he went to the front desk and upgraded our room for an extra $40 a night. It was well worth it we were on the 4th floor overlooking the pool, the room was twice the size of the first room. Overall after that I was pleased. The only negative side of the hotel was the bathrooms, they were small and looked pretty old and could use some remodeling.Other then that, I was really pleased with the hotel room. I mean we couldn't beat the location it was right on Waikiki beach. The restaurants are good, we would eat at Chiefs Hut every morning for the breakfast special since it was only $4.99 everyday and different varieties. The Shorebird was nice, except be prepared to cook your own meat. I think it's fun but others might not agree. They have great lava flows for drinks and entertainment at nighttime.The hotel also has other needs like gift shops and a pantry right on the ground level. This hotel isn't a five star by any means, but if your not to picky and want a hotel close to the beach I recommend this hotel. Would i stay here again? Probably not only because my husband is in the military and we can get fantastic rates at the Hale Koa next door to the Reef. If were weren't though I would consider it again. I've stayed at the Hiliton Hawaiian Village and as standard as the Ohana Islander Hotel so all in all it was