<Content>Outrigger Reef Good News first! We stayed here 6/5/04 - 6/12/04 The lobby is nice with various island gear shops and pantry. Three restaurants, one for pool side dining thoughout the day  evening, The Shorebird which is open air and in a perfect spot facing the ocean, the breakfast buffet was wonderful and the service great! The Ocean, which is more elegant and basically evening dining. We checked in family of five, the hotel clerk was not exactly cheerful, it appeared that she kept me waiting longer than necessary and when she did motion me to step up for my turn not once did she smile. It took her awhile to process my booking info. and give me my promotion packages for my children. I was supposed to get a beach kit with sand bucket according to the package I purchase but that was not given to me. Instead I was given two of the same promotions which was a Big Kahuna canvas tote bag with a CD, etc. Well problem is the promotions was supposed to be for my kids and age appropriate. Anyway, I chose not to say anything because I did not want to get off to a bad start and we were tired from our long day of travel and the kids were excited and wanted to go to the beach. We were given rooms on the 17th floor which is the very top. We had connecting rooms for our three children. The timeshare booth is right behind guest services and I made a big mistake of stopping there to pick-up a coupon book not knowing that it was a timeshare booth. Immediately as I stepped off the elevator on the 17th floor I could see the difference appearance from the lobby. The wallpaper seemed dull and the carpet was old. Our room looked as though it was tidy on first appearance but missing that sparkle. There was food smashed into the carpet that had harden, I sat in the chair and found crumbles along the side of the seat cushion and even a capsule of somekind. May have been a perscribed medication maybe not. Our room had a small kitchenette the microwave was dirty ants was crawling in it. I did not feel comfortable using anything in the cabnet, silverware, coffee cups, dishtowel, nothing. The first night when I was sleeping I felt something crawling on my left ankle but just did not turn on the light. I just brushed it off with my other foot to scared to look afraid of what my reaction would be. That morning as I was coming out of the bathroom I saw something yellow crawling on my pillow and knocked it on the floor. About a minute later I saw another one of the bedspread and picked it up with a piece of paper and flushed it down the toilet. Then another appeared and I lost it and called guest services who transferred me to housekeeping and sent someone up to my room. Where I had put the last one in the toilet and showed it to the housekeeper who barely spoke english but told me it was a TERMITE then she left without saying anything. I called guest services again, and was told that they would send someone to spray. Needless to say, that is what was crawling on me the night before. I searched the kids room and did not see any except the one that someone had stepped on which was smashed into a towel on the floor in front of the shower. I also noticed that the shower (no bathtub) was really small and the ceiling in the bathroom usually low. If I raised my hands over my head to put on my shirt my hands would hit the sealing (I am 5'7) the ceiling must have only been 6'0. The day before we left my husband was checking everywhere in the kids room to make sure that had not forgotten anything and we found an old Gadorade bottle underneath the bed. We had not brought any gadorade so who knows how long that had been under the bed. A few birds left droppings on our balconey a few days earlier and it was never cleaned up so we could not go out and sit on the balconey if we wanted too. The middle elevator was always out of service which caused long waiting periods when you needed to get on. Not to mention that the doors would close abrutly without much of a time delay and if you were not on your mark to jump in the minute the door opened the door would close and the elevator would leave without you. I saw the doors close on a couple of people who were not quick enough. You have to slide your key card in order to select a floor well only the buttons and key card on the right side would work. There was no sign or anything to advise you of this but after the elevator passed your floor enough times and everyone else got off except the people who used the left side we all figured it out on our own. At times the people at the pool shack made you wait in line while they helped people who wanted to buy $200.00 sunglasses and expensive tanning lotions. When all I wanted was a towel. Lastly, there were alot of security guards walking aroung the floors, the pool area, hottub, etc. still could not figure out why all the security? It may me a little uncomfortable wondering should I be on guard, had something happened that I did not know about or was something about to happen? I did not want to dwell on any of the above because I did not want to ruin the fun for anyone. Also, saw big cock roaches crawling aroung in the Chefs Hut restaurant, and at the bar by the pool one fell on a customer who jumped up and started flaling her arms about in front of everyone trying to get the thing off of her. But, I would not stay here again. This was my 2nd trip in 20 months. The first time I stayed at the Outrigger ON the Beach....That was much nicer....One more thing, there were way too many rocks on the beach no wonder they call it the REEF...It is a miracle that we all escaped without spranged ankles walking on all of those rocks in the water. The beach in front of the OUTRIGGER WAIKKI ON THE BEACH does not have rocks and is much better.  
