<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Pretty Disappointed We stayed at the Outrigger Reef 1/1-1/5/04. I have a feeling that, had we stayed at a different time of year, our experience would have been different.However, the lobby was so busy, it was like a constant circus there, with people pitching you for timeshares and selling leis - and it was usually considerable wait to get your car from the valet. The staff seemed over worked and not too eager to please, just eager to get through the line that was inevitably at the front desk.It was so crowded taking the elevator down sometimes proved to be a problem if you were on the middle floors - the elevators were always full.We got what had to be the worst room in the hotel. It was down a little hall behind the ice machine and the utility elevator and was so tiny we could barely fit our luggage in it without tripping over it. (We stayed for a total of two weeks in Hawaii - also on Maui and Kauai). There was no counter in our bathroom - seriously, the vanity was like an airplane bathroom. We don't know why we got this room - as we peeked into the other standard rooms and they were a lot bigger. I asked to pay for an upgrade and it was completely booked - no rooms available. Given that it was torentially raining for two of the four days we were there - the room definitely was a big minus in our stay in Oahu. Again, I did not feel that the staff was very helpful with this issue.There was one smallish pool and on sunny days, it was pretty crowded. The beach was also pretty small and packed. If you plan to have a beach day, I would definitely plan to rent the $30 chair/umbrella, so you can stake out your spot (they will reserven your spot if you want to leave for more than an hour). They run out early - I got one of the last spots at 10 a.m. and the staff said you should get there by 9 to guarantee a spot. With the umbrellas and chairs, there was no room for people who just want to lay down a towel and sunbathe (for free).Its understandable because its a huge city and there are lots of tourists - and it is one of just a few hotels in Waikiki that are directly on the beach. They are probably all crowded. If you want uncrowded beaches you are better off in Maui or Kauai or even the North Shore of Oahu.We did walk on the beach one night and it was beautiful and deserted.The restaurant/bar they have looking over the ocean is a nice place to hang out. They have good food and drinks and good bands playing at night (on the weekends).Another positive was that it is centrally located. It was an easy walk to many great restaurants and shops. It is definitely a vibrant, fun city.We got the room at the Outrigger for a good price through Hotels.com. However, I feel that I wouldn't do that again because I suspect that is why we were stuck in the terrible room (we paid rock bottom prices). Overall the hotel is busy, which was not what I was looking for, but is attractive. Despite my experience, I think its a good value, especially if you just plan to use it as a base to explore Oahu. 
