<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Will try a different hotel next time My fiance' and I just got back from Hawaii a few days ago. The Outrigger Waikiki is very misleading on the room sizes on their web page. You would assume the rooms are a nice size, but they aren't. We requested a partial ocean view room, and the hotel clerk was happy to let us know that we were given an upgrade, free of charge. What we ended up with was a room with a view of the city, which we didn't want because of the noise. Also, our hotel room was right next to the elevator. In fact, when we got off of the elevator, I thought it was a door to a broom closet. It also had a shower stall in the tiniest bathroom I've ever seen, and we requested a room with a tub when we made reservations.When we went back down to the lobby, the same hotel clerk informed us that the hotel had no bath tubs at all, even though we were told they did. We even were willing to pay for a room with a jacuzzi; those were not available. We ended up taking a downgrade; a smaller room with a partial view of the beach, which is what we requested in the first place. The room was so small, there was no room for he and I to move around. I have never seen a bathroom so small in my life. The Outrigger Reef has a special promotion that gives you a free catamaran sail if you stay five nights or longer, which we did. Before our trip, I contacted the hotel to inquire about this, as we should have been eligible. The staff at that time assured me that it would be no problem at all, we would get our free sail info at check in. But when we got there, we were told we couldn't get that either. To save expenses on the trip, we purchased a phone card to make long distance calls-I discovered 3 days into our trip that, even with a phone card, there is a 97 cent charge whenever you pick up the phone to dial a number, phone card or not. The rooms all have balconies, which is wonderful; none of the balconies has an available screen, so you could never keep the patio doors open, because insects could get in. Another tip: If you want your hotel room cleaned early, leave a tip and a small note for housekeeping. Our first day there, our room wasn't cleaned until after 3p.m., but after we left a tip, (which we didn't mind doing) we quickly moved up the food chain, and our room was the 1st one done each day. The timeshare people were a total nightmare. The are like the perfume sprayers at the malls, but 10 times worse. They nearly tackle you as they fast talk you to get your credit card number to sign you up for a pressure breakfast to get you to buy into a time share. No matter how many times you tell them you're not interested, it never ends. We were approached by them at least 30 times in the 6 days we were there. It can be extremely overwhelming. Please shop around for souvenirs; the hotel store is very overpriced. It is on the beach, but be prepared to pay for additional items like umbrella and chair rentals.The hotel is beautiful and spacious, and it was our 1st trip to Hawaii, but we've already decided that when we go back next year, it will be to a different hotel. 
